 or sometimes â€˜venture capitalistâ€™ is the team of people that decide which companies to invest in and then manage them to exit they are often known as the â€˜gpâ€™ or â€˜general partnerâ€™Â  a gp can have multiple funds under management at any one time and they are compensated according to the terms of the gp agreement for each fund which determines the fees and profit share they receiveÂ  i covered this in a little more detail when i answered the question what is venture capital turning to the question du jour the first thing that an lp looks for in a venture capital fund manager is track recordÂ  in venture capital past success is a very good indicator of future success unlike many other asset classesÂ  entrepreneurs like to work with investors who have shown an ability to make money and hence vcs with a good track record stand a better than average chance of getting into the best deals and therefore making more moneyÂ  additionally vcs who have had good success have typically built strong networks on the back of that success and are more able to help their companies with introductions to customers and partners the next thing an lp will look for is to see that the team has worked together beforeÂ  ideally they have all worked together in the same manager and developed a good track record togetherÂ  alternatively if the individuals have worked together in past lives then that might be enough to get the lp comfortable after that the lp will look to the fund structurestrategy â€“ how many investments of what size and in which geographies and sectors the fund manager intends to makeÂ  there are some basics that have to be got right â€“ eg the team needs to be large enough to make the planned number of investments when taking into account their commitments to earlier funds the fees need to be sufficient to cover the planned expenses of the managerÂ  some other elements are more subjective and will appeal differently to different lps â€“ eg which sectors the gp intends to invest in cleantech internet etc finally if the lp is comfortable on the three items above they will start to look to the terms of the venture fund of which the most important by far are the fees typically  of funds under management and the profit share or carried interest typically  of profits often after a basic return has been deliveredÂ  lps look through these percentages to see how much money the partners in the gp will get and as a result larger funds are usually nearer the bottom of the ranges given whilst smaller funds are able to get nearer the topÂ  more successful funds are able to command higher fees and carry the first three items track record team history strategy are typically go or nogo gating items whereas the terms are more of a negotiationÂ  related articles where do vcs get their money from theequitykickercom is venture capital right for your company theequitykickercom what is venture capital theequitykickercom is inlabâ€™s vc  the cure for whatâ€™s ailing the venture capital game dailyfinancecom the right amount of venture capital to raise acquiacom httpwwwgamesbriefcom nicholas lovell the â€œgood vcs get better dealsâ€ is an interesting angle when it comes to luck in other words you could say that the secret to being a good vc is to get lucky once because once you have a reputation for being lucky lps and entrepreneurs want to talk to you of course i donâ€™t believe in luck or rather i believe luck happens and lucky people are those who find ways to be open to lucky situations so vcs more than most need to open to the possibility of black swans and be ready to capitalise on that success httpwwwalanodeacom alanodea guys great work so far my one comment about this recent post is simplay to ask is this not a bit high level for a focus on the games industry and a book not all games industry guys get vc that got to be like  of all games companies raise form institutions moreover i think itâ€™s a bit high level to be talking about where vcâ€™s